n box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Angela Lindsay\n  |votes      = 14,307\n  |percentage = 34.3\n  |change     = -3.2\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 12,521\n  |percentage = 31.4\n  |change     = +6.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 40,865\n  |percentage = \n  |change     = +42.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan Senate District 23 Election, 2006}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer\n  |votes      = 64,404\n  |percentage = 69.8\n  |change     = +16.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Frank Lambert\n  |votes      = 27,931\n  |percentage = 30.2\n  |change     = +16.4\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 36,473\n  |percentage = 39.5\n  |change     = +32.8\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 92,335\n  |percentage = 100\n  |change     = +11.6\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = +16.4\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Michigan State Senate District 23 Election, 2010}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Gretchen Whitmer (Incumbent)\n  |votes      = 49,974\n  |percentage = 64.0\n  |change     = -5.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Kyle Haubrich\n  |votes      = 28,127\n  |percentage = 36.0\n  |change     = +5.8\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  | |votes = 21,847\n  |percentage = 28.0\n  |change     = -11.6\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  | |votes = 78,101\n  |percentage = 100\n  |change     = -15.4\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n| |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n|swing = -5.8\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=Michigan gubernatorial election, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mielections.us/election/results/2018GEN_CENR.html|title=2018 Michigan Official General Election Results - 11/06/2018|website=mielections.us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lwvoa.org/files/LWVOAFullVoterGuideNovember2018-compressed.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116173304/http://www.lwvoa.org/files/LWVOAFullVoterGuideNovember2018-compressed.pdf |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Gretchen Whitmer<br>[[Garlin Gilchrist]]\n |votes = 2,256,791\n |percentage = 53.34%\n |change = +6.48%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Republican Party (United States)|candidate = [[Bill Schuette]]<br>[[Lisa Posthumus Lyons]]|votes = 1,853,650|percentage = 43.81%|change = -7.11%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate = Bill Gelineau <br>Angelique Chaiser Thomas|votes = 56,752|percentage = 1.34%|change = +0.21%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Green Party of the United States|candidate = Jennifer V. Kurland<br>Charin H. Davenport|votes = 28,857|percentage = 0.68%|change = +0.21%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Constitution Party (United States)|candidate = Todd Schleiger<br>Earl P. Lackie|votes = 24,701|percentage = 0.58%|change = -0.03%\n| }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party = Natural Law Party|candidate = Keith Butkovitch<br>Raymond Warner|votes = 10,258|percentage = 0.24%|change = -\n| }}\n{{Election box majority\n| |votes = 403,141\n |percentage = 9.53%\n |change = +5.47%\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n| |votes = 4,231,009\n |percentage =\n |change = 34.04%\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n  | |winner = Democratic Party (US)\n  |loser = Republican Party (US)\n  |swing = \n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Education===\nWhitmer would like to phase in full-day Universal Pre-K for 4-year-olds in Michigan. She also wants to reduce the cost of childcare for struggling families. She would eliminate Michigan's current 3rd grade \"read or flunk\" policy, which she has said penalizes students who have been failed by the education system, and would instead work to improve their reading skills. She proposes that all high school students be offered two years of debt-free higher education, either college or post-secondary training for skilled trades.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bridgemi.com/public-sector/what-michigan-schools-will-look-under-governor-whitmer-or-schuette|title=What Michigan schools will look like under Governor Whitmer or Schuette|date=October 25, 2018|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nWhitmer has said she would fight Republican efforts to take away protections for patients with preexisting conditions. In the State Senate, Whitmer successfully worked to expand Medicaid coverage in the state. She has spoken against single-payer healthcare as unrealistic. She has stated she would work to lower the cost of prescription drugs, and would get rid of Shuette's drug immunity law, which she believes protects drug companies from legal trouble if their drugs harm or kill people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/07/18/michigan-governor-race-gretchen-whitmer-blue-cross/|title=A Blue Cross CEO Encouraged a Michigan Woman to Get Into Politics. Now She's Running for Governor and Says Single Payer Is Unrealistic.|last=Jilani|first=Zaid|date=July 18, 2018|website=The Intercept-US|accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Taxation===\nIn March 2019 Whitmer proposed increasing the gasoline tax 45 cents per gallon to fund road repairs. If it is enacted Michigan will have the highest fuel tax in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2019/03/04/whitmer-budget-road-funding-options/3055987002/|title=Gov. Gretchen Whitmer to propose 45-cent hike in fuel tax to fund Michigan roads|website=Detroit Free Press|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhitmer has two children with her first husband, Gary Shrewsbury. The couple divorced, and in 2011 she married dentist Marc Mallory, who has three children from his previous marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan/2018/06/27/gretch-whitmer-profile-michigan-governor/698088002/|title=Whitmer rises to establishment choice in Democrats' gov race|work=Detroit News|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gretchenwhitmer.com/bio/|title=Meet Gretchen \u2013 Gretchen Whitmer for Governor|work=Gretchen Whitmer for Governor|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref> Whitmer and Mallory live in [[East Lansing, Michigan]], with her two daughters, Sherry and Sydney, and his three sons, Alex, Mason, and Winston.<ref name=\"monprofile\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oaklandlegalnews.com/washtenaw/1423164|title=Monday Profile: Gretchen Whitmer|date=April 11, 2016|work=Oakland Legal News|accessdate=December 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226060218/http://www.oaklandlegalnews.com/washtenaw/1423164|archive-date=December 26, 2016|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wlns.com/news/6-news-on-demand/skubick-whitmer-family-joins-in-run-for-governor/999903055|title=Skubick: Whitmer family joins in run for governor|last=VanderKolk|first=Kevin|date=January 4, 2017|work=WLNS|accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Gretchen Whitmer}}\n* [https://gretchenwhitmer.com/ Campaign website]\n* [http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=37868 Project Vote Smart \u2013 Senator Gretchen Whitmer (MI)] profile\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060526202257/http://www.michiganliberal.com/tag.do?tag=SD23 Michigan Liberal \u2013 SD23]\n* {{C-SPAN|Gretchen Whitmer}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-mi-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=Laura Baird}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]]<br>from the 70th district|years=2001\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Judy Emmons]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael C. Murphy (Michigan politician)|Michael C. Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Michigan House of Representatives]]<br>from the 69th district|years=2003\u20132006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Meadows (Michigan politician)|Mark Meadows]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-mi-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Virgil Bernero]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Michigan Senate]]<br>from the 23rd district|years=2006\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Curtis Hertel Jr.]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Prusi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minority Leader of the [[Michigan Senate]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Ananich]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Schauer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Governor of Michigan]]|years=[[Michigan gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stacey Abrams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Response to the State of the Union address]]|years=[[2020 State of the Union Address|2020]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rick Snyder]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Michigan]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before={{Incumbent VPOTUS}}|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Michigan}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Asa Hutchinson]]|as=[[List of Governors of Arkansas|Governor of Arkansas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Michigan}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ron DeSantis]]|as=[[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Michigan}}\n{{Current U.S. governors}}\n{{Michigan statewide political officials}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitmer, Gretchen}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Michigan House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Michigan Democrats]]\n[[Category:Michigan state senators]]\n[[Category:Michigan State University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Lansing, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Women state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Michigan]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "MyPreferredUsernameWasTaken", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTenure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gretchen_Whitmer"}
{"title_page": "William Van Alstyne", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = William Van Alstyne\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = William Warner Van Alstyne\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1934|02|08}}\n|birth_place = [[Chico, California|Chico]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2019|01|29|1934|02|08}}\n|death_place = [[Huntington Beach, California]], U.S.\n|other_names = \n|spouse      = {{marriage|Carol Frances|1955|1978|end=divorced}}<br /> {{marriage|[[Pamela Gann]]|1981|2002|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Lan Cao]]|2003}}\n|children    = [[Marshall Van Alstyne]]<br/> Allyn Van Alstyne <br/> Lisa Van Alstyne <br/> Harlan Van Cao\n|known_for   = [[Constitutional Law]]<br/>[[Civil Rights]]\n|occupation  = [[Professor]]\n|nationality =\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Southern California]]<br />[[Stanford Law School]]\n}}\n\n'''William Warner Van Alstyne''' (February 8, 1934 \u2013 January 29, 2019) was an [[Law of the United States|American attorney]], [[law professor]], and [[United States constitutional law|constitutional law]] [[scholar]]. Prior to retiring in 2012, he held the [[Professor|named position]] of Lee Professor of Law at [[William and Mary Law School]]. He was the Perkins Professor of Law at Duke Law School for more than 30 years. Among many others, he taught at Chicago Law School, Stanford Law School, University of California, Berkeley Law School, University of California, Los Angeles Law School, and Michigan Law School.\n\nVan Alstyne received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[philosophy]] ''[[Latin honors|magna cum laude]]'' from the [[University of Southern California]]. He received his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Stanford Law School]]. Following his admission to the California Bar and brief service as deputy attorney general of California, he joined the civil rights division of the U. S. department of justice, handling voting rights cases in the South. For many years, he was active in the American Association of University of Professors (AAUP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://academeblog.org/2019/02/26/remembering-william-van-alstyne/|title=Remembering William Van Alstyne|first=Hank Reichman|last=says|date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing active duty with the U. S. Air Force, he was appointed to the law faculty of the Ohio State University, advancing to full professor in three years. Van Alstyne was named to Duke's William R. and Thomas S. Perkins Chair of Law in 1974. He held a certificate from The Hague Academy of International Law and has been honored with LL.D. degrees by Wake Forest University and the College of William and Mary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.law.duke.edu/history/faculty/vanalstyne/|title=William W. Van Alstyne &#124; Duke University School of Law|first1=Duke Law 210 Science Drive Box 90362|last1=Durham|first2=NC 27708|last2=Office613-7006|website=web.law.duke.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Van Alstyne was selected in a poll by the New York Law Journal of federal judges, attorneys, and academics, as one of three academics among \"the ten most qualified\" persons in the country for appointment to the supreme court, a distinction repeated in a similar poll by The American Lawyer, in 1991. Past national president of the American Association of University Professors and former member of the national board of directors of the American Civil Liberties Union, he was elected into the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1994.\n\nVan Alstyne's body of work included many books, [[law journal]] articles, and [[United States Congressional committee|congressional committee]] testimony. In 1994, he was elected into the American Academy of Arts and Sciences. An article in the January 2000 ''[[The Journal of Legal Studies|Journal of Legal Studies]]'' found that Van Alstyne was among the top 40 legal scholars in the United States in number of academic [[citation]]s.<ref>Shapiro, Fred R. \"The Most-Cited Legal Scholars.\" Journal of Legal Studies 29.1 (Jan. 2000): 409-426. 14 July 2007.</ref> His work also had been cited by courts, including the Supreme Court of the United States. In a 2012 study published by the University of Michigan Law Review, by Fred Shapiro and Michelle Pearse, \"The Most-Cited Law Review Article of All Time,\" Van Alstyne's \"The Demise of the Right-Privilege Distinction in Constitutional Law,\" 81 Harv. L. Rev. 1439 (1968), was included at number 35.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Michigan Law Review |volume=110 |issue=8 |page=1490 |title= The Most-Cited Law Review Articles of All Time |url=http://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1084&context=mlr |first1=Fred R.|last1=Shapiro |first2=Michelle |last2=Pearse |year=2012 |accessdate=11 January 2019| format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nHe testified numerous times before congress on numerous constitutional issues. His testimony on the impeachment of President William Jefferson Clinton was quoted with approval by the New York Times opinion page, \"This point [to strike a balance] was underscored by one of the Republican witnesses, Prof. William Van Alstyne of Duke University Law School. It is ''the prerogative of this Congress,'' he observed, ''to express dismay, despair and condemnation'' by means short of impeachment. Mindful of the likelihood that impeachment would fail, he urged lawmakers to ''struggle to find a suitable means to express your sense of disappointment. That neatly defines the challenge now confronting the members of Congress. There is nothing in the Constitution to keep them from rising to that task.\"''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/11/opinion/constitutional-room-for-censure.html |title=Constitutional Room for Censure |date=1998-11-11 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nHe died from heart failure on January 29, 2019, aged 84.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.duke.edu/news/duke-law-mourns-passing-renowned-scholar-william-van-alstyne/|title=Duke Law mourns passing of renowned scholar William Van Alstyne|website=Duke University School of Law}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/05/obituaries/william-van-alstyne-dead.html|title=William Van Alstyne, 84, Dies; Often-Cited Constitutional Scholar|first=Sam|last=Roberts|date=February 5, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|William Van Alstyne}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Alstyne, William Warner}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary faculty]]\n[[Category:Duke University School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:First Amendment scholars]]\n[[Category:Scholars of constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Stanford Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = William Van Alstyne\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|birth_name  = William Warner Van Alstyne\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1934|02|08}}\n|birth_place = [[Chico, California|Chico]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2019|01|29|1934|02|08}}\n|death_place = [[Huntington Beach, California]], U.S.\n|other_names = \n|spouse      = {{marriage|Carol Frances|1955|1978|end=divorced}}<br /> {{marriage|[[Pamela Gann]]|1981|2002|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Lan Cao]]|2003}}\n|children    = [[Marshall Van Alstyne]]<br/> Allyn Van Alstyne <br/> Lisa Van Alstyne <br/> Harlan Van Cao\n|known_for   = [[Constitutional Law]]<br/>[[Civil Rights]]\n|occupation  = [[Professor]]\n|nationality =\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Southern California]]<br />[[Stanford Law School]]\n}}\n\n'''William Warner Van Alstyne''' (February 8, 1934 \u2013 January 29, 2019) was an [[Law of the United States|American attorney]], [[law professor]], and [[United States constitutional law|constitutional law]] [[scholar]]. Prior to retiring in 2012, he held the [[Professor|named position]] of, Lee Professor of Law at [[William and Mary Law School]]. He was the Perkins Professor of Law at Duke Law School for more than 30 years. Among many others, he taught at Chicago Law School, Stanford Law School, University of California, Berkeley Law School, University of California, Los Angeles Law School, and Michigan Law School.\n\nVan Alstyne received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[philosophy]] ''[[Latin honors|magna cum laude]]'' from the [[University of Southern California]]. He received his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Stanford Law School]]. Following his admission to the California Bar and brief service as deputy attorney general of California, he joined the civil rights division of the U. S. department of justice, handling voting rights cases in the South. For many years, he was active in the American Association of University of Professors (AAUP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://academeblog.org/2019/02/26/remembering-william-van-alstyne/|title=Remembering William Van Alstyne|first=Hank Reichman|last=says|date=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing active duty with the U. S. Air Force, he was appointed to the law faculty of the Ohio State University, advancing to full professor in three years. Van Alstyne was named to Duke's William R. and Thomas S. Perkins Chair of Law in 1974. He held a certificate from The Hague Academy of International Law and has been honored with LL.D. degrees by Wake Forest University and the College of William and Mary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.law.duke.edu/history/faculty/vanalstyne/|title=William W. Van Alstyne &#124; Duke University School of Law|first1=Duke Law 210 Science Drive Box 90362|last1=Durham|first2=NC 27708|last2=Office613-7006|website=web.law.duke.edu}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Van Alstyne was selected in a poll by the New York Law Journal of federal judges, attorneys, and academics, as one of three academics among \"the ten most qualified\" persons in the country for appointment to the supreme court, a distinction repeated in a similar poll by The American Lawyer, in 1991. Past national president of the American Association of University Professors and former member of the national board of directors of the American Civil Liberties Union, he was elected into the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1994.\n\nVan Alstyne's body of work included many books, [[law journal]] articles, and [[United States Congressional committee|congressional committee]] testimony. In 1994, he was elected into the American Academy of Arts and Sciences. An article in the January 2000 ''[[The Journal of Legal Studies|Journal of Legal Studies]]'' found that Van Alstyne was among the top 40 legal scholars in the United States in number of academic [[citation]]s.<ref>Shapiro, Fred R. \"The Most-Cited Legal Scholars.\" Journal of Legal Studies 29.1 (Jan. 2000): 409-426. 14 July 2007.</ref> His work also had been cited by courts, including the Supreme Court of the United States. In a 2012 study published by the University of Michigan Law Review, by Fred Shapiro and Michelle Pearse, \"The Most-Cited Law Review Article of All Time,\" Van Alstyne's \"The Demise of the Right-Privilege Distinction in Constitutional Law,\" 81 Harv. L. Rev. 1439 (1968), was included at number 35.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Michigan Law Review |volume=110 |issue=8 |page=1490 |title= The Most-Cited Law Review Articles of All Time |url=http://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1084&context=mlr |first1=Fred R.|last1=Shapiro |first2=Michelle |last2=Pearse |year=2012 |accessdate=11 January 2019| format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nHe testified numerous times before congress on numerous constitutional issues. His testimony on the impeachment of President William Jefferson Clinton was quoted with approval by the New York Times opinion page, \"This point [to strike a balance] was underscored by one of the Republican witnesses, Prof. William Van Alstyne of Duke University Law School. It is ''the prerogative of this Congress,'' he observed, ''to express dismay, despair and condemnation'' by means short of impeachment. Mindful of the likelihood that impeachment would fail, he urged lawmakers to ''struggle to find a suitable means to express your sense of disappointment. That neatly defines the challenge now confronting the members of Congress. There is nothing in the Constitution to keep them from rising to that task.\"''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/11/opinion/constitutional-room-for-censure.html |title=Constitutional Room for Censure |date=1998-11-11 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nHe died from heart failure on January 29, 2019, aged 84.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.duke.edu/news/duke-law-mourns-passing-renowned-scholar-william-van-alstyne/|title=Duke Law mourns passing of renowned scholar William Van Alstyne|website=Duke University School of Law}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/05/obituaries/william-van-alstyne-dead.html|title=William Van Alstyne, 84, Dies; Often-Cited Constitutional Scholar|first=Sam|last=Roberts|date=February 5, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|William Van Alstyne}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Alstyne, William Warner}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary faculty]]\n[[Category:Duke University School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:First Amendment scholars]]\n[[Category:Scholars of constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Stanford Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Kbabej", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor punctuation edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Van_Alstyne"}
{"title_page": "2014 Tennessee gubernatorial election", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2014 Tennessee gubernatorial election\n| country = Tennessee\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2010 Tennessee gubernatorial election\n| previous_year = 2010\n| next_election = 2018 Tennessee gubernatorial election\n| next_year = 2018\n| election_date = November 4, 2014\n| image1 = [[File:Bill Haslam 2016.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1 = '''[[Bill Haslam]]'''\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1 =  '''951,796'''\n| percentage1 = '''70.3%'''\n| image2 = \n| nominee2 = Charles Brown\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2 = 309,237\n| percentage2 = 22.8%\n| map_image = Tennessee Governor Election Results by County, 2014.svg\n| map_size = 300px\n| map_caption = County Results <br/>\n'''Haslam:''' {{legend0|#e27f7f|50\u201360%}} {{legend0|#d75d5d|60\u201370%}} {{legend0|#d72f30|70\u201380%}} {{legend0|#c21b18|80\u201390%}}\n| title = [[Governor of Tennessee|Governor]]\n| before_election = [[Bill Haslam]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Haslam]]\n| after_party = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsTN}}\nThe '''2014 Tennessee gubernatorial election''' took place on November 4, 2014 to elect the [[Governor of Tennessee]]. Incumbent Republican Governor Bill Haslam won re-election to a second term.\n\nHaslam, who was first elected over [[Mike McWherter]] in 2010, defeated Democratic candidate Charles Brown in a landslide, winning 70% of the vote and carrying every county in the state. This was the best performance in a Tennessee gubernatorial election since [[Buford Ellington]]'s victory in [[1966 Tennessee gubernatorial election|1966]].\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n* Mark \"Coonrippy\" Brown<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/06/mark-coonrippy-brown-