ke McWherter]] in 2010, defeated Democratic candidate Charles Brown in a landslide, winning 70% of the vote and carrying every county in the state. This was the best performance in a Tennessee gubernatorial election since [[Buford Ellington]]'s victory in [[1966 Tennessee gubernatorial election|1966]].\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n* Mark \"Coonrippy\" Brown<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/06/mark-coonrippy-brown-raccoon-man-governor_n_4548518.html|title=Mark 'Coonrippy' Brown Runs For Governor To Get His Seized Raccoon Rebekah Back\n|publisher=The Huffington Post |date=January 6, 2014 |accessdate=January 7, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Haslam]], incumbent Governor<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wbir.com/news/article/245982/2/Gov-Bill-Haslam-announces-re-election-campaign |title=Gov. Bill Haslam announces re-election campaign |publisher=wbir.com |date=December 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130618005209/http://www.wbir.com/news/article/245982/2/Gov-Bill-Haslam-announces-re-election-campaign |archivedate=June 18, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Basil Marceaux]], perennial candidate<ref name=tnsos>{{cite web|url=http://tn.gov/sos/election/PetitionsFiled.pdf|title=Petitions Filed for Governor, United States Senate, and United States House of Representatives\n|publisher=Tennessee Secretary of State|accessdate=April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n* Donald McFolin, Independent candidate for Governor [[2010 Tennessee gubernatorial election|in 2010]]<ref name=tnsos/>\n\n====Declined====\n* [[John Jay Hooker]], political [[Social gadfly|gadfly]] and Democratic nominee for governor in [[1970 Tennessee gubernatorial election|1970]] and [[1998 Tennessee gubernatorial election|1998]] (running as an independent)<ref name=candidatescommit>{{cite web|url=http://www.memphisdailynews.com/news/2014/apr/2/candidates-commit-as-deadline-nears/|title=Candidates Commit as Deadline Nears|publisher=[